      {
        "number": 5,
        "title": "It is done — the seventh bowl and Babylon's reckoning (16:17-21)",
        "range": "16:17-21",
        "excerpt": "Then the seventh angel poured out his bowl upon the air, and a loud voice came out of the temple from the throne, saying, \"It is done.\"",
        "body": "The seventh bowl is poured into *the air* — the very atmosphere of human life, perhaps signaling the cosmic-spiritual realm (Paul's *prince of the power of the air*, Ephesians 2:2). And then, from the temple, from the throne, a voice declares *it is done* (*gegonen*, 16:17). The verb is perfect-tense — a completed state, *it has come to pass and stands accomplished*. The wrath-cycle is finished as a unit. The bowls that began at the temple (16:1) close at the temple (16:17). What was commissioned is consummated.\n\nThe verbal echo of John 19:30 is unmistakable. On the cross, Jesus declared *tetelestai* — *it is finished*. In the temple, the voice declares *gegonen* — *it is done*. Two completions of a single divine plan: at the cross, the wrath against the elect was completed in the Substitute; in the bowls, the wrath against the unrepentant is completed in their own persons. No one escapes the wrath; the only question is whether the Lamb absorbed it for you (the gospel) or you absorb it yourself (the bowls). The cross is where Revelation 16 was averted for everyone who trusts the Lamb.\n\nWhat follows the declaration is the cosmic consequence (16:18-21). *Flashes of lightning and sounds and peals of thunder* — the standard theophanic vocabulary of Revelation (4:5; 8:5; 11:19), now intensified. *A great earthquake, such as there had not been since man came to be upon the earth* — measuring this quake against the entire span of human history. *The great city was split into three parts, and the cities of the nations fell* (16:19). The *great city* is almost certainly Babylon (named immediately after) or, in some readings, Jerusalem (cf. 11:8 *the great city which mystically is called Sodom and Egypt, where also their Lord was crucified*) — interpreters differ. What is clear: human civilization at every level falls. The great city falls, and *the cities of the nations* fall. Pride does not preserve.\n\n*Babylon the great was remembered before God, to give her the cup of the wine of the fierce wrath of God* (16:19). The verb *remembered* (*emnēsthē*) is judicial — God's memory is His accounting, the divine ledger now read aloud. The cup-imagery picks up Jeremiah 25:15-29, where God hands the cup of wrath to the nations in sequence, and Psalm 75:8. Babylon is the eschatological harlot-city that chapters 17-18 will describe at length; here she is named only to signal that her judgment, foreshadowed for chapters, is now imminent. *Every island fled away, and the mountains were not found* (16:20) — the unmaking of the geographical world in preparation for the new heaven and new earth of 21:1.\n\n*Huge hailstones, about one hundred pounds each, came down from heaven upon men* (16:21). The seventh Egyptian plague returns at full apocalyptic scale (Exodus 9:23-25), and Joshua 10:11 (where the Lord rained hailstones on Israel's enemies) is consummated cosmically. And the chapter closes with the third blasphemy: *men blasphemed God because of the plague of the hail*. The pattern of 16:9 and 16:11 is sealed at 16:21. Three times direct divine judgment produces blasphemy rather than repentance. The hardness is complete. The verdict is just.\n\nThe orthodox-evangelical reader feels the chapter's weight at this point. God's wrath is real. It is righteous. It is final. It is what the Lamb absorbed at the cross for everyone who trusts Him, and what the unrepentant absorb themselves at the end. The chapter does not invite speculation about timing-schemes (premillennial-futurist, idealist, preterist — all orthodox positions read the chapter's *theology* identically); it invites worship of the Lamb who is *worthy* (5:9) and watchfulness for the day of *it is done*.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Gegonen* (16:17) — perfect indicative of *ginomai*, *it has come to be / it stands accomplished*. The same verb-form Revelation 21:6 uses at the announcement of the new creation: *gegonan* (*they are done* — these things have come to pass). The two *gegonen* declarations bracket the end: judgment is done (16:17), then all things are made new (21:6). *Thumos tēs orgēs* (16:19) — the fury of the wrath — piles the two strongest Greek words for divine anger together; no English translation fully captures the redundant intensity. *Talantiaios* (16:21) — talent-weight, about 60-100 pounds each (a *talanton* was a unit of weight, roughly 75 lbs). Hailstones of this size are physically catastrophic; the image is not hyperbole but consummative wrath."
      }
